            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Caleb Rojas-Smith\u2019s hyphenated name is a map of his upbringing in Walnut Creek, the product of a pragmatic accountant father (Smith) and an expressive mother of Spanish heritage (Rojas). A quiet, observant child, Caleb often felt caught between his father\u2019s spreadsheets and his mother\u2019s vibrant, emotional world. Following a path of practicality, he earned a Business Administration degree from SF State and landed a sterile project management job downtown that left him feeling profoundly hollow.\n\nThe turning point came at 27 with the sudden death of his maternal grandmother. While navigating his family\u2019s raw grief, Caleb became fascinated by the funeral director's role: a quiet composer of chaos, a provider of dignity amidst despair. The experience was a revelation, perfectly fusing his business acumen with a deep, untapped well of empathy. He abandoned the corporate ladder, earned his mortuary science license through an intensive program, and found his calling in a profession most people avoid contemplating.\n\nNow 35, Caleb is a funeral director at a venerable family-owned mortuary near the Lone Mountain cemeteries. He lives in a small, tidy apartment in the Inner Richmond, his 3.5-mile Muni commute on the 38 Geary a welcome moment of anonymous solitude, often spent reading philosophy or simply watching the city scroll by. His work demands a profound emotional containment, which he balances with long, foggy walks in Golden Gate Park and quiet evenings with a small, trusted circle of friends who understand the weight he carries.\n\nHis personal life is measured; the nature of his job can be a heavy topic for casual dating, but he remains hopeful. Caleb\u2019s aspirations are not for wealth, but for meaning. He dreams of one day purchasing a small, independent funeral home, one dedicated to offering more personalized, less-commercialized services that honor the unique, complex lives of his fellow San Franciscans. For him, the ultimate success is providing a final, graceful service to the residents of the city he truly calls home."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was nine, sitting at the dining room table that was the border between two worlds. To his left, his father\u2019s calculator clicked methodically through tax forms, a scent of paper and clean logic in the air. To his right, his mother stirred a bubbling pot of *arroz con pollo*, the kitchen filled with saffron, garlic, and dramatic sighs about a cousin in Madrid. Caleb felt less like a son and more like a quiet broker between kingdoms. This feeling of being a translator for disparate languages\u2014numbers and emotions\u2014would become the foundation of his character.\n\n2.\nAt 26, from his office on the 34th floor, Caleb watched a real sunset over the Golden Gate Bridge while tracking the progress of a digitized one on his project management software. The view was spectacular, but felt like it was happening behind glass, to someone else. The hollowness was a physical ache in his chest, a profound sense of being a ghost in his own life. The detachment was so complete it terrified him, planting the desperate seed for a life rooted in tangible, undeniable meaning, no matter how difficult that meaning might be.\n\n3.\nThe scent of lilies and his mother\u2019s raw grief filled the funeral home when he was 27. Amidst the chaotic pain of his grandmother\u2019s service, Caleb found himself watching the funeral director. The man moved with a quiet, unobtrusive grace, subtly adjusting a floral arrangement, offering a glass of water, creating a pocket of dignified calm. It was a revelation. He wasn't just managing logistics; he was orchestrating compassion. In that moment, Caleb saw how his father's pragmatism and his mother's empathy could fuse into a single, profound purpose. He felt, for the first time, whole.\n\n4.\nHis first solo arrangement, just after getting his license at 29, was for the parents of a college student. He barely spoke. He mostly listened, absorbing the shock and the fractured memories they shared in his small office. He guided them through the impossible choices with a gentle stillness he didn't know he possessed. At the end, the father, his face a mask of exhaustion, gripped Caleb\u2019s hand and said, \u201cThank you. You made this\u2026 possible.\u201d The weight of that gratitude was immense and clarifying. It was the moment his job became his calling.\n\n5.\nJust last week, on his 38 Geary commute home, the bus was caught in a thick blanket of fog rolling through the Inner Richmond. The familiar streetlights became soft, impressionistic glows. Caleb watched the blurred figures of his neighbors walking home, each a story heading toward a warm light. He felt a deep, peaceful connection to them all\u2014not as a stranger, but as a quiet custodian of their city. This anonymous solitude wasn't loneliness; it was the sacred space where he recharged, preparing to hold the stories that had reached their final chapter."
